    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. so i noticed sometimes the crust gets really dark but the inside stays pale. is that just because of the temperature or is there something else happening with the sugars/proteins on the surface specifically? like why does it only happen on the outside?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That uneven browning, where the outside is dark and the inside is still pale, is a classic sign of the Maillard reaction being highly surface-dependent, which is almost always the case when you're baking. It's not just the temperature, though heat is the main driver; it's also about the *concentration* of those sugars and proteins right on the surface, which are exposed to the oven's heat much more intensely than the dough's interior. The heat penetrates slowly, but the surface cooks rapidly, creating a sharp contrast. You could try brushing the dough with a little egg wash or milk before baking, which adds more surface sugars and proteins to encourage a more uniform reaction, though sometimes the unevenness is just part of the charm!",
      "source": "target",
